I was recently listening to [Software Engineering Daily](https://softwareengineeringdaily.com/), and caught [this interview](https://softwareengineeringdaily.com/2017/03/31/webassembly-with-brendan-eich/) with [Brendan Eich](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brendan_Eich), creator of JavaScript and co-founder of Mozilla.
In it he discusses his vision for the future of the web, including his work on [WebAssembly](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WebAssembly) (a faster web language) and [Brave](https://brave.com/) (a new browser).

Brave sounded interesting: it automatically blocks all trackers, mediated ads, and cookies, and [replaces the ads](https://brave.com/about_ad_replacement.html) with its own.
Sounds sketchy, but is actually kind of genius.
Ads that are manually placed by publishers/content creators are left alone (e.g. a static image in the site, amazon affiliate link, shoutout in a podcast), only those that go through the slow loading and [fradulent](http://adage.com/article/digital/ana-report-7-2-billion-lost-ad-fraud-2015/302201/) digital ad mediation industry are replaced.
Once a user has seen/clicked a Brave ad, the revenue is divided up in the following manner:

